            <div class="x6 last">
                <div>
                    <h3 style="margin-bottom: 0;">Shopping &mdash;</h3>
                    <p>Do you want shopping to be as simple as possible? Head on over to Crowfoot Crossing. Not only can you find groceries, big box stores, and restaurants in this shopping district but there is also a Cineplex Odeon theatre if you wanted to catch a movie before finishing off your to-do list. </p>
                    <p>There are two business centres in Silver Springs, one at the western end of the main thoroughfare, Silver Springs Boulevard, and the other immediately north of the gully. The latter has a pub that is now known as the Silver Point, although it is best known by locals as Suds 'n' Spuds.</p>
                    <p>Silver Springs has two shopping plazas that provide people with a variety of services, including convenience stores, fast food restaurants, neighbourhood pubs, beauty salons, liquor stores, doctors' facilities, medication stores, and much more!</p>
                    <p>Spring Hill Plaza is a public space in Spring Hill. The plaza, located at Nosehill Drive and Silver Springs BLVD, provides locals with a local pharmacy, petrol station, a variety of food outlets, a dental clinic, a liquor shop, and more.</p>
                </div>
                <div style="margin-top: 50px;">
                    <h3 style="margin-bottom: 0;">Parks &mdash;</h3>
                    <p>Excellent parks serve society in a variety of ways. Parks promote a healthy lifestyle while also providing enjoyment. They provide a healthy and sanitary communal environment.</p>
                    <p>Parks are connection-building and strengthening areas. Parks encourage inclusiveness and aid in the development of language and interpersonal skills in children. Furthermore, they promote greater awareness of environmental issues.</p>
                    <p>Silver Springs inhabitants are fortunate in that they have a plethora of green spots to choose from for recreation.</p>
                    <p>For your weekend hikes and picnics, you can head over to Bowmont Park. Bowmont Park is located in the northwest area of the city, along the northern bank of the Bow River. The park, which covers around 164 hectares, was established in the early 1980s. The name Bowness Montgomery is a combination of the names of two neighbouring communities.</p>
                    <p>Bowmont Park contains a baseball field and a soccer field. Here you will find paved and unpaved walking paths, off-leash areas for your dog, and beautiful views of the Bow River. The walking paths in this park all connect to Calgary’s Bow River Pathway System giving you ample routes to explore on the weekends.</p>
                    <p>The Botanical Gardens of Silver Springs (BGSS) in Calgary, Alberta, is a true treasure – a one-of-a-kind landscape!</p>
                    <p>The BGSS is accessible to the public from daybreak to twilight year-round and is located within a multi-use zone that began as a Birthplace Forest and now spans several acres of property. There are approximately fourteen gardens in this area, each with its unique qualities. These garden areas are connected by mulched walking routes that run the length of the property. Beautiful floral shrubs and a variety of trees line the pathways leading to the gardens. The gardens show what can grow and thrive in Calgary's northwest.</p>
                    <p>The Silver Springs Community Association is the administrative body for the Silver Springs community garden or 'Edible Garden Group.' The leasing of a garden unit is levied at a minimal annual fee, which is subsequently used to offset the garden's operational costs. An agreement that must be written when leasing a garden box is a perpetual contract, therefore annual extension does not necessitate the signing of a new agreement. It is necessary to be a member of the Silver Springs Community Association.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
